.Dd May 11, 2026
.Dt NOBODY 1
.Os
.Sh NAME
.Nm nobody
.Nd run agents without ambient authority
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Cm run
.Op Fl p Ar policy
.Fl -
.Ar command
.Op Ar argument ...
.Nm
.Cm policy simulate
.Ar policy
.Fl -
.Ar action
.Op Ar argument ...
.Nm
.Cm trace show
.Op Ar latest | file
.Op Fl -jsonl
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a least-privilege execution runtime for AI agents.
The current prototype reads a TOML policy, evaluates process and environment
capability decisions, runs the permitted command with a filtered environment,
prepares the strongest available filesystem sandbox, and appends structured
JSONL trace events.
.Pp
On Linux,
.Nm
uses Landlock to enforce filesystem read/write grants when the policy can be
represented without deny carve-outs beneath granted paths.
The current backend requires fully enforced Landlock ABI v3 filesystem rights.
On other platforms, filesystem policy is diagnostic only and
.Nm
prints a warning before spawning the command.
.Pp
Network, MCP, and browser-control enforcement are planned but are not
implemented in this milestone.
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Fl p , Fl -policy Ar file
Read policy from
.Ar file .
The default is
.Pa nobody.toml .
.El
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width Ds
.It Pa nobody.toml
Default policy file.
.It Pa .nobody/runs/latest.jsonl
Default trace file.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
.Bd -literal
nobody run -- echo hello
nobody run --policy nobody.toml -- echo hello
nobody policy check nobody.toml
nobody policy simulate nobody.toml -- fs.read .env
nobody policy simulate nobody.toml -- process.exec curl
nobody trace show latest
nobody trace show latest --jsonl
.Ed
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Pa docs/policy.md ,
.Pa docs/trace.md ,
.Pa docs/roadmap.md
